│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs in SLPVectorizer during shuffle    │
│ cost finalization with an assertion failure: \"Expected unused subvectors     │
│ mask\". This indicates that, at the point where we merge the common shuffle   │
│ mask with a subvector permutation mask, the code expects SubVectorsMask       │
│ entries to be Poison (unused) wherever CommonMask has a used lane. However,   │
│ in the provided reproducer, both masks can claim the same lane, and the       │
│ assertion triggers.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:\nThe debug log shows a       │
│ complex PHI-heavy graph with multiple bundles and an eventual perfect diamond │
│ match for a gather bundle. The failure happens while computing cost for a     │
│ tree with 17 nodes, specifically when finalizing the gather with subvectors.  │
│ The stack points to BoUpSLP::ShuffleCostEstimator::finalize and the analogous │
│ instruction builder finalize. In finalize, when SubVectorsMask is non-empty,  │
│ the implementation copies it into SVMask and zips it with CommonMask,         │
│ asserting that any used lane in CommonMask must correspond to a Poison entry  │
│ in SubVectorsMask.\n\nThe construction of SubVectorsMask happens in           │
│ processBuildVector, where it is derived via                                   │
│ inversePermutation(E->ReorderIndices) and then partially cleared based on     │
│ whether elements are clustered. However, this construction does not take into │
│ account the current CommonMask content accumulated via prior add() calls.     │
│ Thus, it is possible for SubVectorsMask to mark a lane as used while          │
│ CommonMask also uses that lane, violating the asserted invariant and causing  │
│ a crash.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe invariant enforced in finalize       │
│ assumes that SubVectorsMask only specifies positions in the final vector that │
│ are currently unused in CommonMask. This is not guaranteed by the code that   │
│ builds SubVectorsMask in processBuildVector, which does not reconcile         │
│ SubVectorsMask with the actual CommonMask state. As a result, overlapping     │
│ usage occurs. Since SubVectorsMask is intended to overlay new subvector       │
│ insertions only into unused lanes, the strict assertion is valid              │
│ conceptually, but the earlier logic can produce overlaps.\n\nGiven that       │
│ adjusting the SubVectorsMask upstream requires access to the CommonMask from  │
│ ShuffleBuilder (not available through the current API in processBuildVector), │
│ the pragmatic fix is to make finalize robust to overlaps by skipping the      │
│ overlay for lanes already used in CommonMask instead of asserting. This keeps │
│ the invariant behaviorally intact and avoids crashes.\n\n4. Proposed Edit     │
│ Point(s):\n- Edit Point 1 (Cost Estimator finalize):                          │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp lines 10935-10938.\n  Replace │
│ the assert with a conditional check that only overlays SubVectorsMask entries │
│ when the corresponding CommonMask entry is Poison. This change prevents the   │
│ assertion from firing and correctly ignores overlapping lanes.\n\n  Before:\n │
│ for (auto [I1, I2] : zip(SVMask, CommonMask)) {\n    if (I2 !=                │
│ PoisonMaskElem) {\n      assert(I1 == PoisonMaskElem && \"Expected unused     │
│ subvectors mask\");\n      I1 = I2 + CommonMask.size();\n    }\n  }\n\n       │
